---
import GuideLayout from "../layouts/GuideLayout.astro";
import { guideResources, toolResources } from "../data/content";

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  mainEntity: [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      name: "What grade do I need to pass a class?",
      acceptedAnswer: {
        "@type": "Answer",
        text: "It depends on your current grade, your target grade, and how much coursework remains. This guide shows how to calculate it step by step."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      name: "What is a passing grade?",
      acceptedAnswer: {
        "@type": "Answer",
        text: "Most schools consider 60% or higher a passing grade, but some classes require 70%."
      }
    }
  ]
};

const relatedItems = [
  toolResources.whatGradeDoINeedCalculator,
  toolResources.gradeCalculator,
  toolResources.finalExamCalculator,
  guideResources.isA70PassingGrade,
];
---

<GuideLayout
  title="What Grade Do I Need to Pass a Class?"
  description="Find out what grade you need to pass a class, how to estimate whether your target is realistic, and which calculator to use next."
  slug="/what-grade-do-i-need-to-pass-a-class"
  heroTitle="What Grade Do I Need to Pass a Class?"
  heroText="When you are trying to figure out whether passing is still realistic, the key numbers are your current grade, your target, and how much of the class is still left."
  faqSchema={faqSchema}
  relatedItems={relatedItems}
>
  <div class="card">
    <p>
      One of the most common questions students ask is
      <strong> what grade do I need to pass? </strong>
      The answer depends on your current average, the passing cutoff, and the percentage of the course that has not been graded yet.
    </p>
  </div>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>Start With Three Numbers</h2>
    <ol>
      <li>Your current grade</li>
      <li>Your passing target, such as 60% or 70%</li>
      <li>The percentage of the course that is still remaining</li>
    </ol>
  </section>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>How the Math Works</h2>
    <p>
      You are really asking how strong your remaining work must be to pull your
      class average up to the passing line.
    </p>
    <p class="formula-block">target grade - current contribution = what the remaining work must supply</p>
    <p>
      The <a href="/what-grade-do-i-need-calculator/">What Grade Do I Need Calculator</a>
      does that math automatically.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>Example</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Current grade: 65%</li>
      <li>Passing grade: 70%</li>
      <li>Remaining coursework: 30%</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      In that situation, you need the remaining 30% of the course to lift your
      average enough to reach 70%. Whether that is realistic depends on how many
      assignments or exams are still ahead.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>What If You Need Over 100%?</h2>
    <p>
      If the result comes out above 100%, your target may not be mathematically
      possible with ordinary remaining work alone. You may need extra credit, a
      retake, or help from your teacher to understand your options.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>Helpful Next Steps</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Not sure about your current average? Use the <a href="/grade-calculator/">Grade Calculator</a>.</li>
      <li>If the remaining work is mostly a final exam, use the <a href="/final-exam-calculator/">Final Exam Calculator</a>.</li>
      <li>Wondering whether a 70 counts as passing in your situation? Read <a href="/is-a-70-a-passing-grade/">Is a 70 a Passing Grade?</a></li>
    </ul>
  </section>
</GuideLayout>
